<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-802-346  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 802 346.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  August 1990 v27 n8 p56(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Light that acts like 'natural bits'. (solitons and fiber opticcommunications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bell, Trudy E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Long-haul fiber-optic communications and even optical switchingcould be revolutionized by ultrastable light pulses calledsolitons.andP;  Solitons do not spread in an optical fiber, even aftertraveling thousands of kilometers.andP;  They cancel out chromaticdispersion and the fiber's own nonlinearity, two properties thatdegrade long-distance transmission.andP;  An experiment by AT andamp; T BellLaboratories found that solitons remain stable to recurrentamplifications over 10,000 kilometers.andP;  Spatial solitons in planarwaveguides have the potential of creating integrated all-opticalswitching circuits.andP;  Experiments continue.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Optical CommunicationsSwitchingResearch and DevelopmentFiber OpticsEnhancements.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Soliton wavelengths. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>